as I said this morning , I manually "un-froze it" by triggering an era5 data check.
This is a script that is scheduled to run once/day to reconcile and calculate any "missing" scores if new data has come in from era5.

However, I identified a weakness in the scheduling of this script which meant it could be skipped if there was other work being done in the main event loop at the time of the check. This is why it "froze" over the weekend for era5 scoring. I've since made the scheduling logic more bulletproof so this shouldn't happen again going forward

Its about 15 days until full reward for a forecast run, but a new run starts each day and you can swap out models/fine tunes at any time between runs. You'll be able to compare model results even with day1 scoring, but also with the first era5 lead hours on day ~5-6.

the weight calculation is based on a 15 day lookback of runs, which is then averaged.

So yes, it takes a while for a new miner to move up in score to match existing miners, but I don't see a better approach for the data we want to generate, unless we were to re architect everything and take a ridges-like approach, where models are evaluated on the validator after being posted to an open source repository. I have discussed this option previously and was met with some resistance about open sourcing the whole thing.

Also - what do you mean by "unfair income" ? top miners are there because they have the most complete forecast data, and generally the highest scores in era5 scoring as well. There may be miners with better models who don't quite match in weight yet because their forecast data is less complete, but we need a full evaluation of a forecast run before we can confidently conclude that a model is better or worse.

Do you have any suggestions ?

The benefit to an open source approach is that we can evaluate models more quickly by using hindcasting (setting init time to a day in the past, so that era5 data is already available). We can't do hindcasting with the current architecture because it would be possible for miners to cheat (not easy, but possible)

# Heads up!

a bunch of popular/core npm packages were compromised
https://jdstaerk.substack.com/p/we-just-found-malicious-code-in-the

we highly recommend that you check your npm global install for pm2 to ensure that you don't have a malicious version installed.

you can run this bash script to check versions
```
for pkg in chalk strip-ansi color-convert color-name error-ex simple-swizzle has-ansi \
           ansi-styles ansi-regex wrap-ansi slice-ansi supports-color supports-hyperlinks \
           color-string is-arrayish backslash debug; do
  npm ls -g "$pkg" 2>/dev/null | sed '1d' || true
done
```
compromised versions:
    •    chalk@5.6.1 (maintainers have republished a clean version).  
    •    strip-ansi@7.1.1.  
    •    color-convert@3.1.1.  
    •    color-name@2.0.1.
    •    error-ex@1.3.3.  
    •    simple-swizzle@0.2.3.  
    •    has-ansi@6.0.1.  

Additional Qix-adjacent/related packages confirmed in the same wave: ansi-styles@6.2.2, ansi-regex@6.2.1, wrap-ansi@9.0.1, slice-ansi@7.1.1, supports-color@10.2.1, supports-hyperlinks@4.1.1, chalk-template@1.1.1, color-string@2.1.1, is-arrayish@0.3.3, backslash@0.2.1, and debug@4.4.2.


if any versions match these compromised versions, youll want to stop using npm (and pm2) immediately until you've re-installed non-compromised versions. If you did have a compromised version, be aware that any sensitive information on your machine was likely compromised.

direct bittensor wallet theft was NOT a part of the attack payload, but the payload was designed to exfiltrate as many secrets/env files/ etc as it could find and so should still be taken seriously.

hey, as I have explained previously, this burn is not a temporary thing.

- currently, >60% of the forecasts are duplicates generated from the base model. This provides us no additional value for our product. We have no reason to reward this, though it has been good for us to "stress test" our data handling.

- subnets like ours, which have not begun generating revenue, do not do well without burning or locking a significant amount of emissions. A vast majority of successful subnets now burn or lock some portion of emissions, with many burning more than 80%. 

- When we roll out v.3.0.0 with an updated scoring system, we will revise how we calculate burn. We want to reward miners who beat the base model, and have diverse forecasts specialized to specific regions. We will decide a fair reward rate for miners who meet this criteria, and burn the rest. It's possible that our total burn will actually *increase* in this scenario, but it all depends on the quality of miners outputs. The overall goal is to balance miner reward with the value of the data they generate, instead of just rewarding anyone that can set up a vps and do some config.

I understand that this will upset some people, but I'm afraid we have no option. I've heard all the arguments from the other side, and I'm not convinced by any of them. A subnet must have proper tokenomics for long term success and survival

I agree with @Forward-0318 - there's definitely something wrong with current scoring, which is one of major problems among different ones, which I think - some different ones should have higher priority

First of all, new miners have no chances of surviving after the immunity period - to receive full scoring, you have to wait 25 days (10 days waiting for era5 scoring and 15 runs are being taken for weight calculation), if someone doesn't have the runs calculated, he can't get over the old miners.

This opens a window for Sybil attack, you're able to dominate the subnet and keep deregistering others in order to make them unable to compete with old ones, causing real top miners to deregister, and keeping the malicious ones on the top.

Even more, era5 calculates with random delay, and the runs are being calculated in unexplainable order, which is also causing VTrust to lower, as different validators use the same score for weight calculation, while "the same" score changes in real time (overall_forecast_score) - causing validators to use different ones.

One of possible solutions to it is to make weight calculation at the same time as others validators

Example:
21 utc - your validator calculates era5 240h lead time for latest_run_id - 10, then at 21:50 all validators calculate the weights
22 utc -your validator calculates era5 216h lead time for latest_run_id - 9. then at 22:50 all validators calculate the weights
etc. 

This will clarify from what time the score was taken, which will also make the weight copying work without lowering the VTrust - and most importantly - it will be more clear how the score is being calculated, so miners can evaluate it without guessing what they have to change.

Still, there has to be something changed about the new miners, they are just unable to get into the competition, as they will be always perturbated below top miners

I've done some research and found out that out of all current miners, 134 where harmed (567 different responses) and validator marked some of their runs as "completed" while scoring era5, even though there were remaining lead times to be scored - the cause of that is that validator incorrectly assumes that miner is offline, marking his response in the database with status = "miner_offline" and  error_message = "Miner offline during scoring"

I've used this query:
```sql
SELECT 
    miner_uid,
    COUNT(*) AS occurrence_count
FROM v_weather_miner_responses
WHERE status = 'miner_offline'
GROUP BY miner_uid;
```

Basically, this status is inserted by _cleanup_offline_miner_from_run, which is used in era5 scoring, whenever the miner is registered and function _request_fresh_token returns None

Function _request_fresh_token is supposed to return token, full_zarr_url and manifest_content_hash, which is a result of a handshake and kerchunk request in query_single_miner function - for some reason this doesn't work from time to time and returns None - it can only happen when:
- status_code isn't 2xx
  - miner_communication.py:322
  - miner_communication.py:465
  - miner_communication.py:504
- handshake fails
  - miner_communication.py:432
- connection fails/times out
  - miner_communication.py:533
  - miner_communication.py:546
- HTTP Client failed
  - miner_communication.py:571
- except Exception (unexpected error)
  - miner_communication.py:496
  - miner_communication.py:560


From miner logs, I'm not seeing any difference between a successful score and failed score, which makes me think that miner is incorrectly marked as offline. 

Without validator logs I can't investigate this issue even further - meanwhile I can create a PR, which will add attempts to this section of code - but I'd still like you to take a closer look into what are the errors for those miners, as the fix might be more direct than just a retry block

# Scoring System/ Task Updates Coming Soon

- In the interest of diversifying our datasets, the Gaia team has begun work on some big updates to our incentive mechanism.
- Soon, we will require miners to show measurable improvement in at least one variable or climate region over the base model (Microsoft Aurora). - There will be a limited number of "earning slots" for each category, and the top miner in each will receive the whole reward for that category. The slots will be weighted by importance to human activity (e.g. accuracy in temperate, fertile regions for agriculture is more human-relevant than tundra regions)
- The diversity that this encourages will be helpful for generating probabilistic ensembles that exceed the usefulness of a single foundational model run.
- We will also be introducing at least one more task to build on our weather datasets - **downscaling** is a very important tactic used by local/regional forecasters to improve accuracy for specific regions, and one of the primary challenges in ML weather research at the moment. The global models provide a starting point - and downscaling helps forecasters and industries arrive at a more accurate solution for specific areas, depending on their needs.
- Other potential upcoming tasks include extreme event forecasting, storm path tracking, snowfall and precipitation modeling, etc. 

# Business Development Updates
- Over the past few weeks, the Gaia team has been in contact with multiple public and private organizations in our beautiful home state of Colorado, USA. We are lucky enough to be located amongst the headquarters of several leading atmospheric research organizations as well as private weather companies. We can't say much more yet, but we hope to have some very exciting news to share with you all soon.
- Our belief, shared by many , is that weather data should be publicly and FREELY available. To this end, our current goal is this: construct pipelines that make our entire dataset accessible to research institutions and public forecasting services. Given recent cuts to very important services provided by organizations like the NWS, NOAA, etc - it has never been more important to construct alternative, decentralized solutions that cannot be shut down or manipulated for political gain.
- That doesn't mean that we can't construct proprietary solutions for private industry -and we absolutely intend to do so. Research always precedes valuable industry solutions.

Stay Tuned!
